SIMPLE: hydrazine
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hydrazine
<hw>Hy"dra*zine</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[<ets>Hydr-</ets>
+ <ets>azo-</ets> + <ets>-ine</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>Any
one of a series of nitrogenous bases, resembling the amines and produced
by the reduction of certain nitroso and diazo compounds; <as>as, methyl
<ex>hydrazine</ex>, phenyl <ex>hydrazine</ex>, etc.</as> They are
derivatives of hydrazine proper, <chform>H2N.NH2</chform>, which is a
doubled amido group, recently (1887) isolated as a stable, colorless
gas, with a peculiar, irritating odor. As a base it forms distinct
salts. Called also <altname>diamide</altname>,
<altname>amidogen</altname>, (or more properly
<altname>diamidogen</altname>), etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

